Wow, just wow. We went to the reef tonight to attend a concert that ended up being canceled, so we decided to stay and have dinner. We ate and my wife had 1 drink and water. She went to the restroom, came back and realized she had left her phone, so I followed her back to call it for her if needed. On the way down the hall, she got dizzy, fell over and started having a seizure. An employee saw and says, "we cant have her in here doing that, we need to have her leave." I explained she wasnt drunk, she sas having a medical issue, they said it didnt matter and she cant be laying on the floor. Like she choose to have a seizure and be on the floor? They could see her shaking, they didnt care. I eventually got her to the bench at the top of the 2 flights of stairs. She was sick, lightheaded from the seizure, and had to lay down her head on the bench for a minute. They said I had to get her up, we had to get out. So, I had to help her down 2 flights of stairs right after a seizure while she could barely stand. Out into the rain we went after paying our bill. Thanks a lot for the inhumane treatment. I cant believe they saw her having a seizure, then made sure she got out into the rain. They 100% saw her shaking on the ground, we had been there for over 2 hours, they could check the tab to see dinner and 1 drink for her. Never been kicked out of a place for a medical emergency, the reef will sure make sure you dont stick around if you do. They had 2 or 3 people around us at all times to make sure I got her out of there by myself at all times. Crazy treatment of another human, just crazy

For a summer evening out for dinner and drinks, the Reef's tiki Rooftop lounge in downtown Boise is the place to be one would think. But not sure if it is worth it with the parking and just for one stop for the night.  The Reef offers a great happy hour until 6pm for drinks and a really good deal on appetizers! Although it's hot on the Rooftop that time of day, there are shaded areas.  The concrete table tops make it durable for weather but too hot to touch and melted our drinks quickly.  Service was so so, friendly but not terribly responsive and it wasn't that busy. Pretty par for Boise dining unfortunately.  The Rooftop has its own music and only the live music performances can be heard inside (a cooler place to be in more than one way...lol)  Will have to try it again later in the evening next time and bounce around downtown more.

I'm a huge fan of Tiki bars and enjoy visiting them in my work travels around the US. I was surprised to find this one in Boise, ID. They have the indoor portion of a second floor of a building, plus the rooftop. I was here in early July and the rooftop was beautiful. It was about 90 degrees and the sun didn't set until 9:30 PM. Bartenders were friendly, and a huge variety of tropical drinks to choose from. I was impressed by the Hukilau posters inside, and the Tiki mug collection in the cases outside the hallway to the restrooms. Food was great. Had the wasabi tempura salmon tacos with the Asian slaw and the voodoo fries. It was so yummy.
